football)|Kevin Murray]], was a quarterback at Texas A&M from 1983 to 1986.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/kevin-murray-1.html |title=Kevin Murray College Stats |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 5, 2019}}</ref> His uncle, University of Texas alumnus [[Calvin Murray]], is a former professional baseball player for the [[San Francisco Giants]], [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]], and [[Chicago Cubs]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.wfaa.com/story/sports/high-school/2014/08/21/14219360/ |title=Allen's Kyler Murray follows in dad's footsteps at A&M |date=May 28, 2014 |website=WFAA |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141209210209/http://www.wfaa.com/story/sports/high-school/2014/08/21/14219360/ |archive-date=December 9, 2014 |access-date=May 6, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sports/high-schools/football-news/headlines/20131116-kevin-murray-has-gone-from-one-time-am-star-to-dallas-fort-worth-s-elite-quarterback-coach-with-a-client-list-to-prove-he-may-be-the-best.ece|title=Kevin Murray has gone from one-time A&M star to Dallas-Fort Worth's elite quarterback coach|work=dallasnews.com|accessdate=May 6, 2015}}</ref> Murray is a second-generation [[Korean American]], with his maternal grandmother being a South Korean national.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2014/gatorade-football-poy-kyler-murray-qa |title=Kyler Murray dishes about his dodgeball, The Streak and being a road warrior |date=December 8, 2014 |website=USA Today High School Sports |access-date=December 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of quarterbacks with non-white or non-black ancestry]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{footballstats|nfl=2562382|espn=3917315|pfr=M/MurrKy00}}\n{{baseballstats|mlb=663470|espn=41185|brm=murray001kyl}}\n*[http://www.soonersports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?ATCLID=211452796&DB_OEM_ID=31000 Oklahoma Sooners bio]\n*[https://www.azcardinals.com/team/players-roster/kyler-murray/ Arizona Cardinals bio]\n\n{{Arizona Cardinals roster navbox}}\n{{NFL starting quarterbacks navbox}}\n{{Navboxes| list1=\n{{Texas A&M Aggies quarterback navbox}}\n{{Oklahoma Sooners quarterback navbox}}\n{{Heisman Trophy}}\n{{Davey O'Brien Award}}\n{{AP Players of the Year}}\n{{Manning Award}}\n{{Earl Campbell Tyler Rose Award}}\n{{Big 12 Conference football Player of the Year navbox}}\n{{Gatorade Football Player of the Year}}\n{{Gatorade National Athlete of the Year}}\n{{USA Today OPOY}}\n{{2018 MLB Draft}}\n{{Oakland Athletics first-round draft picks}}\n{{NFL Number One Draft Picks}}\n{{2019 NFL Draft}}\n{{CardinalsFirstPick}}\n{{Arizona Cardinals 2019 draft navbox}}\n{{Arizona Cardinals starting quarterback navbox}}\n{{AP Offensive Rookies of the Year}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Murray, Kyler}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American sportspeople of Korean descent]]\n[[Category:People from Allen, Texas]]\n[[Category:People from Bedford, Texas]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from the Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Texas]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma Sooners football players]]\n[[Category:Texas A&M Aggies football players]]\n[[Category:Heisman Trophy winners]]\n[[Category:Arizona Cardinals players]]\n[[Category:American baseball players of Korean descent]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Texas]]\n[[Category:Harwich Mariners players]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma Sooners baseball players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football quarterback and baseball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name                = Kyler Murray \n| image               = Kyler Murray NFL draft.png\n| image_size          = 225px\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Murray at the 2019 NFL Draft\n| current_team        = Arizona Cardinals\n| number              = 1\n| position            = [[Quarterback]]\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1997|8|7}}\n| birth_place         = [[Bedford, Texas]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| height_ft           = 5\n| height_in           = 10\n| weight_lb           = 207\n| high_school         = [[Allen High School (Texas)|Allen]] ([[Allen, Texas]])\n| college             = [[Oklahoma Sooners football|Oklahoma]]\n| draftyear           = 2019\n| draftround          = 1\n| draftpick           = [[List of first overall National Football League draft picks|1]]\n| pastteams           = \n* [[Arizona Cardinals]] ({{NFL Year|2019}}\u2013present)\n| status              = Active\n| highlights          = \n* [[NFL Offensive Rookie of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[PFWA All-Rookie Team]] ([[PFWA All-Rookie Team#2019|2019]])\n* [[Heisman Trophy]] (2018)\n* [[Davey O'Brien Award]] (2018)\n* [[Associated Press College Football Player of the Year]] (2018)\n* [[Big 12 Conference football individual awards|Big 12 Offensive Player of the Year]] (2018)\n* First-team All-[[Big 12 Conference|Big 12]] ([[2018 All-Big 12 Conference football team|2018]])\n* ''[[USA Today]]'' Offensive Player of the Year (2014)\n* 2\u00d7 [[Mr. Football Award (Texas)|Mr. Texas Football]] (2013, 2014)\n* 2\u00d7 ''USA Today'' All-American ([[2013 USA Today All-USA high school football team|2013]], [[2014 USA Today All-USA high school football team|2014]])\n* [[Gatorade Football Player of the Year]] (2014)\n| statleague = NFL\n| statseason = 2019\n| statweek   = \n| statlabel1 = [[Touchdown|TD]]\u2013[[Interception|INT]]\n| statvalue1 = 20\u201312\n| statlabel2 = Passing yards\n| statvalue2 = 3,722\n| statlabel3 = Completion percentage\n| statvalue3 = 64.4\n| statlabel4 = [[Passer rating]]\n| statvalue4 = 87.4\n| statlabel5 = Rushing yards\n| statvalue5 = 544 \n| statlabel6 = Rushing touchdowns\n| statvalue6 = 4\n| nflnew              = kylermurray/2562382\n| pfr                 = MurrKy00\n}}\n\n'''Kyler Cole Murray''' (born August 7, 1997) is an [[American football]] [[quarterback]] for the [[Arizona Cardinals]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He played [[college football]] for the [[Texas A&M Aggies football|Texas A&M Aggies]] and [[Oklahoma Sooners football|Oklahoma Sooners]]. He also played as an [[outfielder]] for the [[Oklahoma Sooners baseball]] team. He won the 2014 [[Gatorade Football Player of the Year]] award as a senior in high school, and the [[Associated Press College Football Player of the Year]], [[Davey O'Brien Award]], and [[Heisman Trophy]] awards for his 2018 season with Oklahoma, in addition to numerous others.\n\nHe was drafted [[List of first overall National Football League draft picks|first overall]] by the Cardinals in the [[2019 NFL Draft]], as well as ninth overall by the [[Oakland Athletics]] in the [[2018 MLB draft]], making him the only player to ever be drafted in the first rounds of both sports.\n\n==High school career==\n===Football===\nMurray was born in [[Bedford, Texas]], to [[Kevin Murray (American football)|Kevin Murray]] and Misun Henderson.<ref name=\"birth\">''Texas, Birth Index, 1903-1997''</ref> He attended [[Allen High School (Allen, Texas)|Allen High School]] in [[Allen, Texas]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2018/12/06/heart-texas-kyler-murray-fans-are-rooting-an-oklahoma-qb-win-heisman/ |title=In the heart of Texas, Kyler Murray fans are rooting for an Oklahoma QB to win the Heisman |last=Wallace |first=Ava |date=December 6, 2018 |website=Washington Post |language=en |access-date=March 5, 2019}}</ref> As a senior in 2014, he was the [[Gatorade Football Player of the Year]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://highschoolsportsblog.dallasnews.com/2014/12/kyler-murray-presented-national-gatorade-player-of-the-year-award-at-surprise-ceremony-in-allen.html/ |title=Kyler Murray presented National Gatorade Player of the Year award at surprise ceremony in Allen |last=Smith |first=Corbett |website=High School Sports Blog |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150627203800/http://highschoolsportsblog.dallasnews.com/2014/12/kyler-murray-presented-national-gatorade-player-of-the-year-award-at-surprise-ceremony-in-allen.html/ |archive-date=June 27, 2015 |access-date=May 6, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://usatodayhss.com/2014/kyler-murray-named-gatorade-national-football-player-of-the-year |title=Kyler Murray named Gatorade National Football Player of the Year |last=Konecky |first=Chad |website=USA Today High School Sports |access-date=May 6, 2015}}</ref> His team won three straight state championships and 43 games in a row. He missed one start during this streak and finished his career with a perfect 42\u20130 record as a starting quarterback.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.foxsports.com/southwest/story/allen-qb-kyler-murray-completes-perfect-career-with-third-state-title-122014 |title=Allen QB Kyler Murray completes perfect career with third state title |date=December 21, 2014 |website=FOX Sports |access-date=May 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMurray was ranked by [[ESPN]], [[Scout.com]], and [[247Sports]] as a five-star recruit and the best [[dual-threat quarterback]] in his class.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/footballrecruiting/football/recruiting/player-Kyler-Murray-138389|title=Kyler Murray|work=yahoo.com|accessdate=May 6, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://recruiting.scout.com/player/174745-kyler-murray/analysis|title=Scout Recruiting \u2013 National Signing Day Coverage, Latest Commits, Top Prospects and More Front Page|work=scout.com|accessdate=May 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150202044216/http://recruiting.scout.com/player/174745-kyler-murray/analysis|archive-date=February 2, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> In May 2014, he committed to [[Texas A&M University]] to play [[college football]] and [[college baseball]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/college-sports/recruiting/football/story/_/id/10997032/top-ranked-qb-kyler-murray-commits-texas-aggies |title=Top-ranked QB Kyler Murray commits to Texas A&M Aggies |last=Hamilton |first=Gerry |website=ESPN.com |access-date=May 6, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/college-football/campus-union/2014/05/28/kyler-murray-commits-texas-am|title=Kyler Murray, four-star QB recruit in the class of 2015, commits to Texas A&M|author=Zac Ellis|work=SI.com|accessdate=May 6, 2015}}</ref><ref name=optout/> He officially signed with them on February 4, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blog.chron.com/sportsupdate/2015/02/star-quarterback-kyler-murray-officially-signs-with-texas-am/#29395103=0&30271101=0 |title=Star quarterback Kyler Murray officially signs with Texas A&M |last=Zwerneman |first=Brent |website=Sports Update |access-date=May 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Statistics====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! colspan=\"6\"|Passing !! colspan=\"4\"|Rushing\n|-\n! {{abbr|Cmp|Pass completions}} !! {{abbr|Att|Pass attempts}} !! {{abbr|Pct|Pass completion percentage}} !! {{abbr|Yds|Passing yards}} !! {{abbr|TD|Passing touchdowns}} !! {{abbr|Int|Passing interceptions}} !! {{abbr|Att|Rush attempts}} !! {{abbr|Yds|Rushing yards}} !! {{abbr|Avg|Rushing yards per attempt}} !! {{abbr|TD|Rushing touchdowns}}\n|-\n! 2012 !! Allen\n| 153 || 249 || 61.40 || 2,040 || 17 || 5 || 188 || 1,370 || 7.30 || 25\n|-\n! 2013 !! Allen\n| 207 || 325 || 63.7 || 3,669 || 46 || 9 || 151 || 1,274 || 8.4 || 19\n|-\n! 2014 !! Allen\n| 278 || 433 || 64.2 || 4,713 || 54 || 8 || 151 || 1,495 || 9.9 || 25\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Total !! 638 !! 1,007 !! 63.4% !! 10,386 !! 117 !! 22 !! 490 !! 4,139 !! 8.4 !! 69\n|-\n| colspan=\"12\"|Source:<ref>{{cite web |url=https://247sports.com/Player/Kyler-Murray-24020?Institution=20589|title=Kyler Murray 247Sports Profile|date=October 30, 2015}}</ref>\n|}\n\n{{College athlete recruit start|40=yes|collapse=no|year=2015}}\n{{College athlete recruit entry\n| recruit = Kyler Murray\n| position = [[Quarterback|QB]]\n| hometown = [[Allen, Texas]]\n| highschool = [[Allen High School (Allen, Texas)|Allen HS]]\n| feet = 5 \n| inches = 9\n| weight = 177\n| 40 = 4.5\n| commitdate = May 28, 2014\n| scout stars = 5\n| rivals stars = 4\n| 247 stars = 5\n| espn stars = 5\n}}\n{{College athlete recruit end\n| 40 = \n| year = 2015\n| rivals ref title = Texas A&M Football Commitments\n| scout ref title = 2015 Texas A & M College Football Recruiting Commits\n| espn ref title = ESPN\n| rivals school = tamu\n| scout s = 187\n| espn schoolid = 37\n| scout overall = 9 (QB)\n| rivals overall = 5 (QB)\n| espn overall = 1 ([[Dual-threat quarterback|Dual-threat QB]])\n| accessdate = October 30, 2015\n}}\n\n===Baseball===\nMurray also played [[baseball]] and was considered one of the top prospects for the [[2015 Major League Baseball draft]]. In high school, Murray was a [[shortstop]] and a [[second baseman]]. He was the first player to ever be selected for both the [[Under Armour All-America Baseball Game]] and [[Under Armour All-America Game|Under Armour All-America Football Game]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/draft/kyler-murrays-journey-chicago-armour/|title=Kyler Murray Has Wild Journey To Become First Two-Sport Under Armour All-American|work=BaseballAmerica.com|accessdate=May 6, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://highschoolsportsblog.dallasnews.com/2014/05/mlb-draft-might-be-the-biggest-hurdle-in-getting-allen-qb-kyler-murray-to-texas-am.html/|title=MLB Draft might be the biggest hurdle in getting Allen QB Kyler Murray to Texas A&M|work=High School Sports Blog|accessdate=May 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\n===Football===\n====Texas A&M====\n{{see also|2015 Texas A&M Aggies football team}}\nAs a true freshman in 2015, Murray competed with [[Kyle Allen]] before the season for the starting quarterback position.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/sec/post/_/id/101306/texas-ams-qb-battle-between-kyle-allen-kyler-murray-will-soon-begin |title=Texas A&M's QB battle between Kyle Allen, Kyler Murray will begin soon |last=Khan Jr. |first=Sam |date=May 6, 2015 |website=[[ESPN]] |access-date=November 2, 2015}}</ref> Allen won the job, with Murray appearing in games as a backup (primarily on plays involving the [[wildcat formation]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/college-football/2015/08/24/texas-am-aggies-kyle-allen-starting-quarterback|title=Texas A&M names sophomore Kyle Allen starting quarterback|date=August 24, 2015|website=[[Sports Illustrated]]|accessdate=November 2, 2015}}</ref> After the team lost two straight games in October, the competition was opened again prior to the [[2015 South Carolina Gamecocks football|South Carolina]] game, and Murray won the starting quarterback position.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blog.chron.com/sportsupdate/2015/10/texas-am-turns-to-kyler-murray-at-quarterback/ |title=Texas A&M turns to Kyler Murray at quarterback |last=Zwerneman |first=Brent |date=October 30, 2015 |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |access-date=November 2, 2015}}</ref> In his first start, Murray threw for 223 yards and rushed for 156 yards with a passing touchdown and a rushing touchdown, making him and [[Cam Newton]] the only [[Southeastern Conference]] quarterbacks in the past 20 years to gain over 100 yards passing and rushing, including a passing touchdown and a rushing touchdown in their first career start.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://collegesports.blog.statesman.com/2015/11/01/ams-kyler-murray-pulls-off-rare-sec-feat-in-debut/ |title=A&M\u2019s Kyler Murray pulls off rare SEC feat in debut |last=Halliburton |first=Suzanne |date=November 1, 2015 |website=[[Austin American-Statesman]] |access-date=November 2, 2015}}</ref> On December 24, 2015, Murray announced that he was transferring to the [[University of Oklahoma]]. Per NCAA transfer rules, he had to miss the 2016 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/ncaaf-dr-saturday/former-texas-a-m-qb-kyler-murray-signs-with-oklahoma-202030505.html;_ylt=A0LEVi3OVXxWSEwAJKJjmolQ |title=Former Texas A&M QB Kyler Murray signs with Oklahoma |last=Cooper |first=Sam |website=Yahoo! Sports |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Oklahoma====\n====2017 season====\n{{see also|2017 Oklahoma Sooners football team}}\n[[File:Kyler Murray vs Texas Oct 6, 2018.png|thumb|264x264px|Kyler Murray vs Texas October 2018]]\nIn the 2017 season, Murray was a backup quarterback to [[Baker Mayfield]]. He got the opportunity to play in some games in relief of Mayfield. He made his season debut in the season opener against [[2017 UTEP Miners football|UTEP]]. In the 56\u20137 victory, he came into the game in the second half and finished 10-of-11 for 149 yards and a touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2017-09-02-oklahoma.html |title=UTEP at Oklahoma Box Score, September 2, 2017 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 30, 2017}}</ref> Two weeks later, against [[2017 Tulane Green Wave football|Tulane]], he hit all three pass attempts for 103 yards and a touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2017-09-16-oklahoma.html |title=Tulane at Oklahoma Box Score, September 16, 2017 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 30, 2017}}</ref> On November 25, against [[2017 West Virginia Mountaineers football|West Virginia]], he started the game after Mayfield had to sit out some of the game due to disciplinary actions in the previous game against the [[2017 Kansas Jayhawks football team|Kansas Jayhawks]]. In the game, he hit both pass attempts for 52 total yards and a touchdown while contributing 80 rushing yards on three carries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2017-11-25-oklahoma.html |title=West Virginia at Oklahoma Box Score, November 25, 2017 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2018 season====\n{{see also|2018 Oklahoma Sooners football team}}\nWithout Mayfield, Oklahoma considered Murray and [[Austin Kendall]] to start at quarterback in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://apnews.com/3021b8001ee64a3381de269290730e2a |title=Oklahoma still looking for QB to replace Mayfield |last=Brunt |first=Cliff |date=April 24, 2018 |website=AP NEWS |access-date=September 19, 2019}}</ref> Murray was chosen as the starting quarterback.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://newsok.com/article/5605578/unique-circumstances-meant-murray-had-to-start-opener/ |title=Finally, OU quarterback job is Kyler Murray's to lose |last=Tramel |first=Barry |date=August 22, 2018 |website=NewsOK.com |access-date=September 19, 2019}}</ref> He threw for more than 4,000 yards and 40 touchdowns in the 2018 regular season. In December 2018, Murray was awarded the [[Heisman Trophy]] as the best collegiate football player in the country, giving Oklahoma back-to-back Heisman winners.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/25484945/kyler-murray-second-straight-oklahoma-quarterback-win-heisman-trophy |title=Murray 2nd straight Sooners QB to win Heisman |last=Harvey |first=Coley |date=December 8, 2018 |access-date=December 9, 2018 |publisher=ESPN |language=en}}</ref> Murray helped lead Oklahoma to a [[2018 Big 12 Championship Game|Big 12 Championship]] and an appearance in the [[College Football Playoff]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2808658-kyler-murray-throws-3-tds-oklahoma-beats-texas-to-win-2018-big-12-championship |title=Kyler Murray Throws 3 TDs, Oklahoma Beats Texas to Win 2018 Big 12 Championship |last=Wells |first=Adam |date=December 1, 2018 |website=Bleacher Report |language=en |access-date=March 5, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crimsonandcreammachine.com/2018/12/2/18122208/oklahoma-sooners-football-college-football-playoff-alabama-orange-bowl-georgia-ohio-state |title=Oklahoma is in the College Football Playoff! |last=Shields |first=Jack |date=December 2, 2018 |website=Crimson And Cream Machine |access-date=March 5, 2019}}</ref> In the [[2018 Orange Bowl]] against [[2018 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]], he had 308 passing yards and two passing touchdowns as the Sooners fell by a score of 45\u201334.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2812993-tua-tagovailoa-alabama-beat-kyler-murray-oklahoma-to-advance-to-cfp-title |title=Tua Tagovailoa, Alabama Beat Kyler Murray, Oklahoma to Advance to CFP Title |last=Kasabian |first=Paul |date=December 29, 2018 |website=Bleacher Report |language=en |access-date=March 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMurray became only the third [[Heisman Trophy]] winner to not be awarded consensus All-American honors.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.si.com/college/alabama/bamacentral/this-wasn-t-the-first-time-the-heisman-winner-wasn-t-a-consensus-all-american-ZWWMCCRVPEmx3dOkSgj3ww |title=This wasn't the first time the Heisman winner wasn't a consensus All-American |website=SI.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===College football statistics===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Legend\n|-\n| style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"|\n| Led the Big 12\n|-\n| style=\"background:#E0CEF2; width:3em\"|\n| Big 12 record\n|-\n| style=\"background:#afe6ba; width:3em;\"|\n| Led the NCAA\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ff0; width:3em;\"|\n| NCAA Record\n|-\n| '''Bold'''\n| Career high\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! colspan=\"7\"|Passing !! colspan=\"4\"|Rushing\n|-\n! {{abbr|Cmp|Pass completions}} !! {{abbr|Att|Pass attempts}} !! {{abbr|Pct|Pass completion percentage}} !! {{abbr|Yds|Passing yards}} !! {{abbr|TD|Passing touchdowns}} !! {{abbr|Int|Passing interceptions}} !! {{abbr|Rate|Passer rating}}!! {{abbr|Att|Rush attempts}} !! {{abbr|Yds|Rushing yards}} !! {{abbr|Avg|Rushing yards per attempt}} !! {{abbr|TD|Rushing touchdowns}}\n|-\n! [[2015 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2015]] !! [[2015 Texas A&M Aggies football team|Texas A&M]]\n| 72 || 121 || 59.5 || 686 || 5 || 7 || 109.2 || 53 || 335 || 6.3 || 1\n|-\n! [[2016 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2016]] !! [[2016 Oklahoma Sooners football team|Oklahoma]]\n| colspan=\"11\" |''Did not play due to NCAA transfer rules''\n|-\n! [[2017 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2017]] !! [[2017 Oklahoma Sooners football team|Oklahoma]]\n| 18 || 21 || 85.7 || 359 || 3 || '''0''' || '''276.5''' || 14 || 142 || '''10.1''' || 0\n|-\n! [[2018 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2018]] !! [[2018 Oklahoma Sooners football team|Oklahoma]]\n| '''260''' || '''377''' || style=\"background:#cfecec;\"| '''69.0''' || style=\"background:#cfecec;\"| '''4,361''' || style=\"background:#cfecec;\"| '''42''' || 7 || style=\"background:#E0CEF2;\"| 199.2 || '''140''' || '''1,001''' || 7.2 || '''12'''\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Total !! 350 !! 519 !! 67.4 !! 5,406 !! 50 !! 14 !! 181.3 !! 207 !! 1,478 !! 7.1 !! 13\n|}\n\n===Baseball===\nMurray opted out of the MLB draft after deciding to attend Texas A&M.<ref name=\"optout\">{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/story/_/id/12833272/top-ranked-qb-signee-kyler-murray-opts-mlb-draft |title=Top-ranked A&M QB signee Kyler Murray opts out of MLB draft |last=Khan Jr. |first=Sam |date=May 6, 2015 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=May 6, 2015}}</ref> He was initially set to play as an [[infielder]] for the [[Texas A&M Aggies baseball|Texas A&M Aggies baseball team]] in the [[2016 Texas A&M Aggies baseball team|2016 season]] until he announced his departure from Texas A&M on December 17, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2015/05/top_qb_recruit_kyler_murray_sa.html |title=Top QB recruit Kyler Murray says he'll play at Texas A&M, bypass MLB draft |last=Stephenson |first=Creg |date=May 6, 2015 |website=[[The Birmingham News]] |access-date=November 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMurray played for the [[Oklahoma Sooners baseball]] team in 2017 as a [[left fielder]]. He had a .122 [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]] and six [[runs batted in]] (RBIs) in 27 games.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Aber |first1=Ryan |title=Sooners' Kyler Murray picked No. 9 by A's in MLB Draft, likely to continue football career |url=https://newsok.com/article/5596989/sooners-kyler-murray-picked-no.-9-by-as-in-mlb-draft-likely-to-continue-football-career |website=NewsOK.com |accessdate=December 13, 2018 |date=June 5, 2018}}</ref> After the 2017 season, he played [[collegiate summer baseball]] for the [[Harwich Mariners]] of the [[Cape Cod Baseball League]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Jen McCaffrey |url=https://theathletic.com/735133/2018/12/27/on-cape-cod-kyler-murray-recalled-as-baseball-prospect-with-potential/ |title=On Cape Cod, Kyler Murray recalled as baseball prospect with potential |publisher=theathletic.com |date=December 27, 2018 |accessdate=September 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Steve Derderian |url=https://www.capecodtimes.com/sports/20181210/heisman-trophy-winner-murray-played-for-harwich-mariners |title=Heisman Trophy winner Murray played for Harwich Mariners |publisher=capecodtimes.com |date=December 10, 2018 |accessdate=September 25, 2019}}</ref> In 2018, playing as a [[centerfielder]], Murray batted .296 with 10 [[home run]]s, 47 RBIs, and 10 [[stolen base]]s.\n\nDespite Murray's reported intention to continue his football career,<ref>{{Cite web|last=Cooper|first=Sam|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/kyler-murray-says-will-play-football-oklahoma-2018-142209566.html|title=Kyler Murray says he will play football for Oklahoma in 2018|website=Yahoo Sports|date=June 5, 2018|access-date=June 19, 2018}}</ref> the [[Oakland Athletics]] selected Murray with the ninth overall selection of the [[2018 MLB draft]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Trotter|first=Jake|url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/23698545/kyler-murray-oklahoma-sooners-chosen-no-9-mlb-draft|title=Sooners QB Kyler Murray chosen No. 9 by Oakland in MLB draft|website=ESPN.com|date=June 5, 2018|access-date=June 19, 2018}}</ref> He signed a contract with the Athletics which included a $4.66&nbsp;million signing bonus.<ref name=JLee61518>{{Cite web|last=Lee|first=Jane|url=https://www.mlb.com/athletics/news/kyler-murray-signs-with-athletics/c-281361954|title=Two-sport star Murray comes to terms with A's|website=MLB.com|date=June 15, 2018|accessdate=June 19, 2018}}</ref> Prior to his junior year with the football team, Murray said that he would report to spring training in 2019 to begin his professional baseball career.<ref name=JLee61518/> However, following his Heisman Trophy-winning 2018 season, he would forgo his senior year and enter the NFL Draft. The A's retain his rights, should he return to baseball.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/american-football/47204411 |title=Kyler Murray commits to pursuing NFL career and turns back on baseball |date=February 11, 2019 |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nIn January 2019, Murray announced that he would enter the [[2019 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/nfl/draft2019/story/_/id/25761371|title=Murray off to NFL draft, but can still consider A's|date=January 14, 2019|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=January 14, 2019}}</ref> On February 11, he announced his decision to focus on his football career, forgoing baseball.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kyler Murray says he's fully committed to becoming an NFL quarterback |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/draft2019/story/_/id/25973188/kyler-murray-says-fully-committed-being-nfl-quarterback |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=February 11, 2019 |date=February 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSome believed that Murray's pursuit of a football career at the expense of a potential one in baseball was a mistake because of his limited stature relative to a typical NFL quarterback.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcsports.com/washington/redskins/kyler-murray-making-mistake-choosing-football-over-baseball-according-joe-theismann|title=Kyler Murray is 'making a mistake' choosing football over baseball, according to Joe Theismann|publisher=NBC Sports|first=Peter|last=Halley|date=January 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.foxsports.com/watch/undisputed/video/1441235011717 |title=Rob Parker: Kyler Murray is making a \u2018colossal mistake\u2019 choosing the NFL over baseball |publisher=FOX Sports |access-date=June 5, 2019}}</ref> At the [[NFL Scouting Combine|NFL Combine]], Murray was not expected to match his listed height of 5'10\",<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ftw.usatoday.com/2019/01/kyler-murray-nfl-draft-height-tall-oklahoma-football-baseball-size-oakland-a |title=Exactly how tall is Kyler Murray anyway? |last=Martinelli |first=Michelle R. |date=January 15, 2019 |website=USA Today |access-date=June 5, 2019}}</ref> because colleges often exaggerate measurements to make players more attractive to professional teams. Murray's final measurements were 5'10 1/8\" and 207 pounds,<ref name=\"sanchez20190228\">{{Cite news |url=https://nypost.com/2019/02/28/kyler-murrays-moment-of-truth-hes-taller-than-we-thought/ |title=Kyler Murray\u2019s moment of truth: He\u2019s taller than we thought |last=Sanchez |first=Mark W. |date=February 28, 2019 |work=New York Post |access-date=October 16, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> similar to that of [[Seattle Seahawks]] starting quarterback [[Russell Wilson]]. Despite not taking part in individual drills at the combine, many saw Murray's draft stock improve because of his greater-than-expected measurements.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesrecordnews.com/story/sports/nfl/2019/03/05/nfl-combine-report-kyler-murray-wins-just-stepping-scale-draft-winners-losers-position-by-position/3059353002/|title=NFL Combine report: Kyler Murray wins just by stepping on a scale; Winners, losers of event|publisher=Wichita Falls Times Record News|first=Jonathan|last=Hull|date=March 5, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/draft/news/2019-nfl-draft-kyler-murray-d-k-metcalf-jamel-dean-win-combine-jachai-polite-has-bad-week-in-indy/|title=2019 NFL Draft: Kyler Murray, D.K. Metcalf, Jamel Dean win combine, Jachai Polite has bad week in Indy|publisher=CBS Sports|first=Ryan|last=Wilson|date=March 5, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsok.com/article/5624351/murray-standing-tall-at-5-foot-10|title=Kyler Murray wins the NFL Combine|publisher=The Oklahoman|first=Berry|last=Tremel|date=February 28, 2019}}</ref> In contrast, [[NFL Network]] reporter [[Charley Casserly]] said that Murray had \"the worst report I\u2019ve ever heard on a top-ranked quarterback from the interview part of it\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/03/06/worst-report-ive-ever-heard-nfl-network-analyst-crushes-kyler-murray/|title=\u2018The worst report I\u2019ve ever heard\u2019: NFL Network analyst crushes Kyler Murray|work=The Washington Post|first1=Des|last1=Bieler|first2=Cindy|last2=Boren|date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> though Murray's agent disputed this report.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/03/06/kyler-murrays-agent-unloads-on-charley-casserly/|title=Kyler Murray\u2019s agent unloads on Charley Casserly|publisher=Pro Football Talk|first=Mark|last=Florio|date=March 6, 2019}}</ref> [[Gil Brandt]] also questioned the veracity of Casserly's assertions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Gil_Brandt/status/1103794668855156736|title=About this Kyler Murray situation: 1) Only 1 team put him in front of white board. 2) The questions about leadership, study habits run counter to my experience w/ Kyler, who I've known since he was a HS soph. Have known his dad for 30 years. Honestly, it all sounds fabricated.|website=Twitter|first=Gil|last=Brandt|date=March 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{NFL predraft\n| height ft    = 5\n| height in    = 10\u215b\n| weight       = 207\n| dash         = \n| ten split    = \n| twenty split = \n| shuttle      =\n| cone drill   = \n| vertical     = \n| broad ft     = \n| broad in     = \n| bench        = \n| wonderlic    = 20\n| arm span     = 28 1/2\n| hand span    = 9 1/2\n| note         = All values from NFL combine<ref>{{cite web|title=Kyler Murray Combine Profile|url=https://www.nfl.com/prospects/kyler-murray?id=32194d55-5267-0413-8d36-a5c3fd781aa0|publisher=NFL.com|accessdate=August 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://thespun.com/college-football/the-wonderlic-scores-for-nfl-drafts-top-prospects-have-leaked |title=The Wonderlic Scores For NFL Draft\u2019s Top Prospects Have Leaked |website=thespun.com |access-date=June 5, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\nMurray was drafted first overall by the [[Arizona Cardinals]] in the 2019 NFL Draft,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001027977/article/kyler-murray-drafted-no-1-overall-by-arizona-cardinals |title=Kyler Murray drafted No. 1 overall by Arizona Cardinals |last=Patra |first=Kevin |date=April 25, 2019 |website=NFL.com |access-date=June 5, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001021155/article/quinnen-williams-cant-miss-mcsorleys-comp-qbs-are-a-puzzle|title=Quinnen Williams shows out; McSorley's comp; QBs are a puzzle|publisher=NFL.com|first=Kimberly|last=Jones|date=March 5, 2019}}</ref> becoming the shortest quarterback drafted in the first round ([[Johnny Manziel]] was 5'11\" 3/4\").{{r|sanchez20190228}} When leading [[Texas Tech Red Raiders football|Texas Tech]]'s football program, Cardinals head coach [[Kliff Kingsbury]] said that he would hypothetically spend the draft's top selection on Murray.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/2019-nfl-draft-heres-why-kyler-murray-should-play-in-the-nfl-and-pass-on-baseball/|title=2019 NFL Draft: Here's why Kyler Murray should play in the NFL and pass on baseball|first=Ryan|last=Wilson|date=January 10, 2019}}</ref> The pick made Murray the first player to be drafted in the first round of both the NFL and MLB drafts,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/draft/2019/04/25/nfl-draft-2019-kyler-murray-arizona-cardinals-pick/3573590002/ |title=Kyler Murray selected by Cardinals as NFL draft's No. 1 pick in historic move |last=Middlehurst-Schwartz |first=Michael  |website=USA TODAY |language=en |access-date=April 27, 2019}}</ref> the first time that two quarterbacks from the same university have gone in the first round in successive seasons after [[Baker Mayfield]] was selected first in the [[2018 NFL Draft]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/nfl-draft-2019-kyler-murray-makes-history-as-arizona-cardinals-select-quarterback-with-no1-pick-a4126921.html |title=Kyler Murray makes history as Cardinals draft quarterback with No1 pick |last=Ouzia |first=Malik |date=April 26, 2019 |website=Evening Standard |language=en |access-date=April 27, 2019}}</ref> and the first quarterback under 6 feet selected number one in an NFL draft.\n\n===2019 season: Rookie year===\nMurray played his first NFL game on September 8, 2019 against the [[2019 Detroit Lions season|Detroit Lions]], finishing with 308 passing yards, two touchdowns, and an interception as the game ended in a 27\u2013all tie.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001052827/article/kyler-murray-shows-off-potential-in-rallying-cardinals-to-tie |title=Kyler Murray shows off potential in rallying Cardinals to tie |last=Trotter |first=Jim |date=September 8, 2019 |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=September 9, 2019}}</ref> Murray led the Cardinals to a comeback in the fourth quarter from a 16-point deficit, joining [[Jake Plummer]] as the only Cardinals rookie quarterbacks to throw for 300 yards and two touchdowns since the AFL-NFL merger in 1970.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/nfl/story/_/id/27572745/kyler-overcomes-rough-start-rally-cards-tie |title=Kyler overcomes rough start to rally Cards to tie |last=Weinfuss |first=Josh |date=September 9, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=September 19, 2019}}</ref> During Week 2 against the [[2019 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]], Murray finished with 349 passing yards as the Cardinals lost 17\u201323.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.abc15.com/sports/kyler-murray-shines-but-cardinals-rally-comes-up-short-in-loss-to-ravens |title=Kyler shines, but Cardinals come up short vs. Ravens |last=Dale |first=Shane |date=September 15, 2019 |website=KNXV |language=en |access-date=September 19, 2019}}</ref> In Week 4 against the [[2019 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]], Murray threw for 241 yards and a pick-six and rushed four times for 27 yards and his first NFL rushing touchdown in the 27\u201310 loss.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128064 |title=Seahawks grind to 27-10 win over Cardinals |date=September 29, 2019 |agency=Associated Press|website=www.espn.com |access-date=September 29, 2019}}</ref> In the next game against the [[2019 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]], Murray threw for 253 yards and rushed for 93 yards and a touchdown in the 26\u201323 victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127958 |title=Kyler Murray leads Cardinals to 1st win, 26-23 over Bengals |date=October 6, 2019|agency=Associated Press |website=www.espn.com |access-date=October 6, 2019}}</ref> During Week 6 against the [[2019 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]], Murray threw for 340 yards and three touchdowns and rushed 11 times for 32 yards in a narrow 34\u201333 victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128126 |title=Cardinals beat Falcons 34-33 after Bryant's extra point miss |date=October 13, 2019|agency=Associated Press |website=www.espn.com |access-date=October 13, 2019}}</ref> He was named the NFC Offensive Player of the Week for his performance.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001066228/article/sam-darnold-kyler-murray-among-players-of-the-week |title=Sam Darnold, Kyler Murray among Players of the Week |last=Baca |first=Michael |date=October 16, 2019 |website=www.nfl.com |access-date=October 16, 2019}}</ref> In Week 10, against the [[2019 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]], he had 324 passing yards, three touchdowns, and one interception in the 30\u201327 loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://cardswire.usatoday.com/2019/11/10/kyler-murray-rookie-record-passes-interception/ |title=Kyler Murray sets 2 records in loss to Buccaneers |date=November 10, 2019 |website=Cards Wire |language=en |access-date=November 19, 2019}}</ref> In Week 11 against the [[2019 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]], Murray threw for 150 yards and two touchdowns and rushed for 67 yards and a touchdown in the 36\u201326 loss. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128089 |title=49ers rally past Cardinals 36-26 on 4 TD passes by Garoppolo |date=November 17, 2019 |website=www.espn.com|agency=Associated Press |access-date=November 17, 2019}}</ref> In Week 16 against the Seattle Seahawks, Murray threw for 118 yards and a touchdown and rushed for 40 yards before exiting the game due to a hamstring injury. Without Murray, the Cardinals won the game 27\u201313.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127941 |title=Cardinals roll past playoff-bound Seahawks in 27-13 victory |date=December 22, 2019|agency=Associated Press |website=www.espn.com |access-date=December 22, 2019}}</ref> Before the regular season finale against the [[2019 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]], Murray was listed as a game time decision with a hamstring injury and ultimately played in the game despite being hurt.  During the game, Murray threw for 325 yards, two touchdowns, and two interceptions during the 31\u201324 loss. Afterwards, Cardinals' head coach [[Kliff Kingsbury]] said that \"It's the most proud I've been of him all season.\" <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128038 |title=Rams say goodbye to Coliseum with 31-24 win over Cardinals |date=December 29, 2019|agency=Associated Press |website=www.espn.com |access-date=December 29, 2019}}</ref> \n\nMurray finished his rookie season with 3,722 passing yards, 20 passing touchdowns, and 12 interceptions to go along with 544 rushing yards and four rushing touchdowns on 93 carries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/M/MurrKy00/gamelog/2019/ |title=Kyler Murray 2019 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2020}}</ref> At the NFL Honors on February 1, Murray won the AP NFL Offensive Rookie of the Year Award for his performance during the season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/nfl-honors-cardinals-kyler-murray-wins-offensive-rookie-of-the-year-beating-out-josh-jacobs-a-j-brown/|title=NFL Honors: Cardinals' Kyler Murray wins Offensive Rookie of the Year, beating out Josh Jacobs, A.J. Brown|website=CBSSports.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/28586997/nfl-honors-took-home-league-biggest-awards |title=NFL Honors: Who took home the league's biggest awards? |date=February 1, 2020|agency=NFL Nation |website=www.espn.com |access-date=February 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===NFL statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Team\n! colspan=\"2\"| Games\n! colspan=\"8\"| Passing\n! colspan=\"4\"| Rushing\n! colspan=\"2\"| Fumbles\n|-\n! GP !! GS !! Comp !! Att !! Pct !! Yds !! Avg !! TD !! Int !! Rtg !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! TD !! Fum !! Lost\n|-\n! [[2019 NFL season|2019]] || [[2019 Arizona Cardinals season|ARI]]\n| 16 || 16 || 349 || 542 || 64.4 || 3,722 || 6.9 || 20 || 12 || 87.4 || 93 || 544 || 5.8 || 4 || 5 || 2\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! colspan=\"2\"|[http: