kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} || {{convert|310|Nm|0|abbr=on}} || {{convert|210|km/h|1|abbr=on}} || 9.0 sec || 1997\u20132001 || 184 g/km\n|}\n\n===Safety===\nIn the [[Euro NCAP]] safety and crash tests, the Audi B5 A4 received 3&nbsp;stars for front- and side-impact protection, but the last star is flagged to indicate that the driver may be subjected to a high risk of chest injury in the side impact.<ref name=\"euroncap.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.euroncap.com/tests/audi_a4_1997/14.aspx |title=Audi A4 |accessdate=1 June 2008 |work=EuroNCAP.com}}</ref>\n*Adult occupant = {{rating|3|5}}\n*Pedestrian = {{rating|2|4}} (pre 2002 rating)\n\n===Derived hybrid version===\nIn 1997, Audi was the first European car manufacturer to put a [[hybrid vehicle]] into [[mass production]], the third generation Audi duo, then based on the A4 Avant.<ref>Audi.com [http://www.audi.com/audi/com/en2/about_audi_ag/news/press_echo/Audi_Q7_hybrid___making_a_clean_start.html Audi Q7 hybrid \u2013 making a clean start]{{failed verification|date=March 2012}}</ref><ref>Audi.com [http://www.audi.com/audi/aola/cr/about_audi_ag/company_perspective/design/studies/q7_hybrid_concept/hybrid_history.html Audi Q7 hybrid concept \u2013 15 years of pioneering work]{{failed verification|date=March 2012}}</ref>{{Clear}}\n\n=={{anchor|B6|8E|8H}}B6 (''Typ'' 8E/8H; 2001\u20132006)== \n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Second generation (B6/8E/8H)\n| image = Audi A4 B6 Avant black.JPG\n| aka = \n| production = 2000\u20132006 (Europe)<br/>2003\u20132005 (China; [[FAW-Volkswagen|FAW-VW]])\n| model_years = 2001\u20132005<br/>2002\u20132006 (convertible)\n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| body_style = 4-door [[sedan (automobile)|saloon/sedan]]<br/>5-door Avant ([[station wagon|estate/wagon]])<br/>2-door [[Convertible (car)|Cabriolet]]\n| platform = [[Volkswagen Group B platform#B6|Volkswagen Group B6 (PL46) platform]]\n| engine = {{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Inline-four petrol engine\n|1 = 1.6L [[inline-four engine|I4]]\n|2 = 1.8L I4 20v [[turbocharger|Turbo]]\n|3 = 2.0L I4 [[multi-valve|20v]]\n|4 = 2.0L I4 [[gasoline direct injection|FSI]] 16v\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = V6 petrol engine\n|1 = 2.4L [[V6 engine|V6]] 30v\n|2 = 3.0L V6 30v\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = V8 petrol engine\n|1 = 4.2L [[V8 engine|V8]] 40v\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Inline-four diesel engine\n|1 = 1.9L I4 [[Turbocharged Direct Injection|TDI]]\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = V6 diesel engine\n|1 = 2.5L V6 TDI\n}}\n| transmission = {{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Manual Transmission\n|1 = 5-speed [[Manual Transmission|Manual]]\n|2 = 6-speed Manual\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Automatic Transmission\n|1 = 5-speed [[Automatic Transmission|Automatic]]\n|2 = 6-speed Automatic\n}}\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2650|mm|1|abbr=on}},<br/>Cabriolet: {{convert|2654|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|4547|mm|1|abbr=on}},<br/>Avant: {{convert|4544|mm|1|abbr=on}}; Cabriolet: {{convert|4573|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|1766|mm|1|abbr=on}},<br/>Cabriolet: {{convert|1777|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|1428|mm|1|abbr=on}},<br/>Cabriolet: {{convert|1391|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| weight = \n| related = [[Audi S4#B6]]\n| designer = [[Peter Schreyer]] (1997)<br />[[Luc Donckerwolke]] (Avant)\n| sp = uk\n}}\n\n{{multiple image | align = left | direction = vertical | width = 200\n| image1 = 2001-2005 Audi A4 (8E) 2.0 sedan 03.jpg\n| caption1 = Sedan\n| image2 = 2002-2005 Audi A4 (8E) 2.0 Avant (2011-10-25) 02.jpg\n| caption2 = Avant\n| image3 = Audi A4 B6 Cabriolet 02 China 2014-04-28.jpg\n| caption3 = Cabriolet\n}}\n\nThe next A4, internally designated '''''Typ'' 8E''', debuted on 10 October 2000, now riding on the [[Volkswagen Group B platform#B6|Volkswagen Group B6 (PL46) platform]]. The car's new styling was developed under Peter Schreyer between 1996\u20131998, inspired by the Bauhaus design language of the C5 (second-generation) [[Audi A6]] introduced in 1997. The 1.6-litre base model powerplant remained unchanged, but most other [[petrol engine|petrol/gasoline engines]] received either displacement increases, or power upgrades. The 1.8-litre 20-valve [[turbocharger|Turbo]] was now available in two additional versions, with {{convert|150|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} or {{convert|180|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}, this one with a standard six-speed [[manual gearbox]], while the naturally aspirated 1.6-litre [[inline-four engine]] and 2.8-litre [[V6 engine|V6]] were replaced by 2.0-litre, and all-[[aluminium alloy]] 3.0-litre units, still with five valves per cylinder, the most powerful of which was capable of {{convert|220|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|300|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} of torque. The 1.9 [[Turbocharged Direct Injection]] (TDI) engine was upgraded to {{convert|130|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}, with [[Unit Injector|Pumpe D\u00fcse (Unit Injector)]] (PD) technology, and was now available with [[quattro (four wheel drive system)|quattro]] permanent [[four-wheel drive]], while the 2.5 [[V6 engine|V6]] TDI high-end model was introduced with {{convert|180|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} and standard quattro. This generation of quattro consisted of default of 50:50 front to rear dynamic torque distribution. A [[Robert Bosch GmbH|Bosch]] ESP&nbsp;5.7 [[electronic stability control|Electronic Stability Programme]] (ESP) system, with [[anti-lock braking system]] (ABS), [[brake assist]], and [[electronic brakeforce distribution]] (EBD) were standard across the range.\n\nThe Avant was introduced in June 2001 and arrived in European showrooms in September 2001.{{citation needed|date=February 2014}}\n\nFor 2002, Audi increased power in the 1.8 Turbo engines to {{convert|183|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|190|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} \u2013 the 190&nbsp;PS variant designated by a red 'T' on the boot lid. Available with four wheel drive and in the 2.5 TDI intermediate version to {{convert|163|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}. A 2.0 engine with [[gasoline direct injection|Fuel Stratified Injection]] (FSI) was also available. A year later, Audi reintroduced the S4, now powered by a {{convert|344|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} 4.2&nbsp;L [[V8 engine]], as well as an A4 Cabriolet [[convertible (car)|convertible]] variant ('''''Typ'' 8H'''), finally replacing the [[Audi 80|80]]-based Audi Cabriolet which had been discontinued in 2000. It included an electro-hydraulic operated roof, which lowered in under 30 seconds and incorporated some styling changes, such as body-coloured lower bumper and sill panels, which later found their way to the saloon version.\n\nAudi introduced a [[continuously variable transmission]] developed by [[LuK]], named [[multitronic]], which replaced the dated conventional automatic transmission on [[front-wheel drive]] models. The transmission won considerable praise from the automotive press, and is generally regarded{{by whom|date=February 2014}} as being the best of its type in the world, due to its light weight and promptness in response.{{citation needed|date=February 2014}} This high strength chain driven CVT was made from highly durable metals and used a very high grade, purpose-designed fully synthetic lubricant. However, there have been widespread complaints from consumers around the world that the transmission box is prone to electronic glitches as well as mechanical problems.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.audi-gearbox-problems.co.uk |title= Audi Gearbox Problems |accessdate=2012-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.audi-forums.com/b6-forum/47603-cvt-reality-check.html|title=CVT reality check|accessdate=2012-04-15}}</ref>\n\nBorrowing from the [[Audi A6]], the boot was redesigned to remove the extension of the top edge with a smoother fold line. The rear light assemblies now formed part of the top line, these styling cues were eventually borrowed by other European as well as Asian manufacturers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boldride.com/ride/2000/audi-a4#gallery/4 |title=Audi A4 specification |date=2011 |access-date=29 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409145742/http://www.boldride.com/ride/2000/audi-a4#gallery/4 |archive-date=9 April 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nA sport package named 'Ultra Sport' was introduced in the North American market shortly before the B6 was replaced by the B7. It included aluminium interior trim and door sills, [[Audi S and RS models#S line|\"S line\"]] steering wheel, front and rear spoilers, side skirts, and [[quattro GmbH]] designed 18-inch RS4 alloy wheels.\n\n===Engines===\nThe following engines were available:\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n! [[internal combustion engine|engine]] type || cyl. || max. power\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" |'''''[[petrol engine]]s'''''<br/><small>all [[fuel injection|fuel injected]]</small>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| 1.6 || [[inline-four engine|I4]] || {{convert|102|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on|lk=on}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| 1.8 Turbo 20v || I4 || {{convert|150|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| 1.8 Turbo 20v|| I4 || {{convert|163|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| 1.8 Turbo 20v 'S line' || I4 || {{convert|163|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| 1.8 Turbo 20v 'S line' || I4 || {{convert|190|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|2.0 20v || I4 || 136 PS (100&nbsp;kW; 134&nbsp;bhp)\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|2.0 FSI || I4 || 150 PS (110&nbsp;kW; 148&nbsp;bhp)\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| 2.4 30v BDV ||[[V6 engine|V6]] || {{convert|170|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| 3.0 30v || V6 || {{convert|220|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| S4 4.2 40v || [[V8 engine|V8]] || {{convert|344|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" |'''''[[diesel engine]]s'''''<br/><small>all [[Turbocharged Direct Injection]] (TDI)</small>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|1.9 TDI || I4 ||{{convert|100|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|1.9 TDI ||I4 ||115 PS (85&nbsp;kW; 113&nbsp;bhp)\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|1.9 TDI ||I4 ||133 PS (96&nbsp;kW; 131&nbsp;bhp)\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| 2.5 V6 TDI 24v || V6 || {{convert|155|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|2.5 V6 TDI 24v ||V6 ||163 PS (120&nbsp;kW; 161&nbsp;bhp)\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|2.5 V6 TDI 24v ||V6 ||180 PS (132&nbsp;kW; 178&nbsp;bhp)\n|}\n\n===Safety===\nThe Audi A4 (B6 & B7) passed the [[Euro NCAP]] safety and crash tests, and was awarded the following car safety ratings:<ref name=\"euroncap.com/\">{{cite web|url=http://www.euroncap.com/tests/audi_a4_2001/88.aspx|title=Audi A4|accessdate=1 June 2008|work=EuroNCAP.com| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080705173823/http://www.euroncap.com/tests/audi_a4_2001/88.aspx| archivedate= 5 July 2008 |url-status = live}}</ref>\n*Adult occupant = {{rating|4|5}}\n*Pedestrian = {{rating|1|4}} (pre 2002 rating)\nThe [[Insurance Institute for Highway Safety]] (IIHS) awarded both the B6 & B7 a \"Good\" rating in the frontal crash test; the B7 was not retested since the front portion is structurally the same.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iihs.org/ratings/rating.aspx?id=163 |title=IIHS-HLDI: Audi A4 |publisher=Iihs.org |date=24 October 2007 |accessdate=11 October 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101105114830/http://www.iihs.org/ratings/rating.aspx?id=163| archivedate= 5 November 2010 |url-status = live}}</ref>{{Clear}}\n\n=={{anchor|B7}}B7 (''Typ'' 8E/8H; 2004\u20132009)==\n{{Infobox automobile\n|name = Third generation (B7/8E/8H)\n|image = 2005 Audi A4 T S Line 1.8 Front.jpg\n|aka =\n|production = 2004\u20132008 (sedan)<br>2007\u20132009 (cabriolet)<br/>2006\u20132009 (China; [[FAW-Volkswagen|FAW-VW]])\n|predecessor =\n|body_style = 4-door [[sedan (automobile)|saloon/sedan]],<br/>5-door Avant ([[station wagon|estate/wagon]]),<br/>2-door [[Convertible (car)|Cabriolet]]\n|platform = [[Volkswagen Group B platform#B7|Volkswagen Group B7 (PL46) platform]]\n|engine = {{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Inline-four petrol engine\n|1 = 1.6L [[inline-four engine|I4]]\n|2 = 1.8L I4 20v [[turbocharger|Turbo]]\n|3 = 1.8L I4 [[multi-valve|16v]] T[[gasoline direct injection|FSI]]\n|4 = 2.0L I4 20v\n|5 = 2.0L I4 16v T[[gasoline direct injection|FSI]]\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = V6 petrol engine\n|1 = 3.2L [[V6 engine|V6]] 24v [[gasoline direct injection|FSI]]\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Inline-four diesel engine\n|1 = 1.9L I4 [[Turbocharged Direct Injection|TDI]]\n|2 = 2.0L I4 TDI\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = V6 diesel engine\n|1 = 2.5L [[V6 engine|V6]] TDI\n|2 = 2.7L V6 TDI\n|3 = 3.0L V6 TDI\n}}\n|transmission = {{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Manual Transmission\n|1 = 5-speed [[Manual transmission|Manual]]\n|2 = 6-speed Manual\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Automatic Transmission\n|1 = 6-speed [[ZF Friedrichshafen|ZF 6&nbsp;hp]] [[Automatic transmission|Tiptronic]]\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Continuously Variable Transmission\n|1 = 7-speed [[Continuously variable transmission|Multitronic]]\n}}\n|wheelbase = {{convert|2648|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n|length = {{convert|4586|mm|1|abbr=on}},<br/>Cabriolet: {{convert|4573|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n|width = {{convert|1772|mm|1|abbr=on}},<br/>Cabriolet: {{convert|1777|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n|height = {{convert|1427|mm|1|abbr=on}},<br/>Cabriolet: {{convert|1518|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n|weight =\n|related = [[Audi S4#B7|Audi S4 (B7)]],<br/>[[Audi RS4#B7|Audi RS4 (B7)]]<br/>[[SEAT Exeo]]\n|designer = [[Walter de Silva]] (2002, 2003)\n|successor=[[Audi A5]] (for A4 cabriolet)\n|sp = uk\n}}\n\n{{multiple image | align = left | direction = vertical | width = 200\n| image1 = 2005 Audi A4 (8EC) 2.0 TFSI quattro sedan (2015-07-10) 02.jpg\n| caption1 = Sedan\n| image2 = Audi A4 Avant (B7) \u2013 Heckansicht, 12. M\u00e4rz 2011, D\u00fcsseldorf.jpg\n| caption2 = Avant\n| image3 = 2006-2009 Audi A4 (8HE) 3.2 FSI convertible (2011-06-15) 02.jpg\n| caption3 = Cabriolet<ref>The competitor: [[BMW 3 Series (E90)|BMW E93]] Convertible</ref>\n| image4 = Audi A4 B7 Avant 2.0 TDI Interieur.JPG\n| caption4 = Interior\n}}\n\nAudi introduced a revised A4 in late 2004, with the internal designation of '''[[Volkswagen Group B platform#B7|B7]]'''. Although given a new platform designation, the B7 was essentially a heavily facelifted and revised version of the B6, with revised steering settings, suspension geometry,{{specify|date=February 2014}} new [[internal combustion engine]] ranges, navigation systems and chassis electronics (including a new advanced [[Robert Bosch GmbH|Bosch]] ESP&nbsp;8.0 [[electronic stability control|Electronic Stability Programme]] (ESP) system). The front grille assembly changed to a tall trapezoidal shape in the same manner as the C6 (third-generation) [[Audi A6]]; however, the dashboard and interior were virtually unchanged from the B6 aside from minor detailing.\n\nAudi's internal platform nomenclature uses PL46 ('''p'''assenger car '''l'''ongitudinal platform, size '''4''', generation '''6''') for both B6 and B7 chassis. The '''''Typ'' 8E''' and '''''Typ'' 8H''' internal designations are also carried over from the B6 A4 range, but now have an additional identifying suffix \u2013 8EC for the saloon, 8ED for the Avant, and 8HE for the Cabriolet.\n\nThe engine lineup received many additions. The 2005 introduction of [[gasoline direct injection|Fuel Stratified Injection]] (FSI) on the 2.0 TFSI and 3.2 [[V6 engine|V6]] FSI [[petrol engine|petrol/gasoline engines]], as well as other refinements, increased power output to {{convert|200|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|255|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}, respectively. These engines both use a four-valve per cylinder configuration. The prior 5-valve design was incompatible with the FSI direct injection system (due to the siting of the fuel injector, now discharging directly into the combustion chamber). The 2.0 [[Turbocharged Direct Injection]] (TDI) [[diesel engine]] now combined [[Unit Injector|Pumpe D\u00fcse (Unit Injector)]] (PD) technology with 16 valves, while the larger 2.5 TDI V6 diesel was superseded by a 3.0 V6 TDI, offering a {{convert|204|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} model during the year 2005 which was upgraded to a {{convert|233|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} model in 2006. A 2.7 V6 TDI was added later.\n\n[[Torsen]] T-2 based [[quattro (four wheel drive system)|quattro]] permanent [[four-wheel drive]] remained as an option on most A4 models. Audi retired its 5-speed [[manual transmission]]s in favour of a new [[Getrag]] 6-speed. As before, [[multitronic]] [[continuously variable transmission]] (CVT), now with selectable 'seven-speeds', was an option on front-wheel drive models, whilst a conventional [[ZF Friedrichshafen|ZF]] [[list of ZF transmissions#6-speed auto|6HP 6-speed]] [[tiptronic]] [[automatic transmission]] was an option on the quattro [[four-wheel drive]] models.\n\nIn addition to the [[Audi S4]], which carried over the [[powertrain]] from the B6 S4 \u2013 Audi reintroduced the [[quattro GmbH]] developed [[Audi RS4]] ('''RS''' for '''''R'''enn'''S'''port'') to the lineup, for the first time on the [[sedan (automobile)|saloon/sedan]] and [[Convertible (car)|Cabriolet]] body, and with a naturally aspirated, but high-revving 4.2-litre [[V8 engine|V8]] FSI engine. Another notable{{according to whom|date=February 2014}} inclusion on the RS4 is the latest generation [[Torsen]] T-3 quattro 4wd system, which uses a 'default' asymmetric 40:60 front-rear dynamic torque distribution bias. This new asymmetric centre differential was initially only available on the RS4, but was added a year later on the S4. The remainder of the B7 A4 range still used the T-2 50:50 default dynamic split centre diff.\n\n[[File:Audi A4 DTM Edition front.JPG|thumb|left|Audi A4 DTM Edition]]\n\nA variant, developed by [[quattro GmbH]], was first introduced in May 2005, named \"Audi A4 DTM [[special edition|Edition]]\". It was inspired from Audi's race cars of the 2004 [[Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters]], and was reintroduced in 2006 as a regular option. The 2.0T FSI engine received revised software mapping to the ECU, which increased the output to {{convert|220|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|300|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} of torque. It was available with front-wheel drive, or quattro four-wheel drive.\n\nThe B7 Cabriolet model arrived later than the other two body variants, with sales beginning in February 2006. New on the Cabriolet was an entry-level 2.0 TDI version, which was not offered with the multitronic CVT gearbox.\n\nIn 2007 Audi introduced a version of the B7 named the 'Special Edition', which built on the S-Line specification and also included the black optics pack, the RS4 style 8J X 18 '7-arm double spoke' design alloy wheels, Two-tone Graphite/Black Volterra leather, 3-spoke sports leather/Alcantara multi-function steering wheel with gear knob and hand brake\nhandle in Alcantara with silver stitching, ventilated cross-drilled front disc-brakes, black tailpipes and black roof rails (Avant model only). It also had a power increase of 20 PS, giving an output of 220 PS on the 2.0T model.\n\nAccording to 2007 Swedish vehicle inspection data, the Audi A4 Avant with [[diesel engine]] is the most reliable vehicle available on the market, with vehicle inspection rejection rate of 0.0% in three-year-old category.<ref>[http://www.tuulilasi.fi/valokeila/?subarea=uutiset&article=149985&page=2 Car unserviceabilities frequency sequence] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081218221850/http://www.tuulilasi.fi/valokeila/?subarea=uutiset&article=149985&page=2 |date=18 December 2008 }}{{Failed verification|date=March 2012}}</ref>\n\n===SEAT Exeo===\n{{Main|SEAT Exeo}}\n\nWhen the successor B8 A4 range was introduced, the B7 series A4 was restyled and [[rebadged]] as the [[SEAT Exeo]] in 2008 with changes to the front and rear plus interior trim from the A4 Cabriolet. The entire Audi B7 A4 production line from Audi's [[Ingolstadt]] [[list of Volkswagen Group factories|plant]] was dismantled and sent to [[Volkswagen Group]]'s related [[SEAT]] factory in [[Martorell]], Spain.<ref name=\"exeo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.carmagazine.co.uk/Drives/Search-Results/First-drives/SEAT-Exeo-first-drive/|title=Seat Exeo (2009) CAR review|last=Kirk|first=Julian|date=4 November 2008|work=Car Magazine|accessdate=13 January 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Engines===\nThe following engines were available:\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size: 96%;\"\n|-\n!engine type<br/>/ drive!!max. power!![[sedan (automobile)|saloon]]!![[station wagon|Avant]]!![[Convertible (car)|Cabriolet]]!!0-{{convert|100|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}<br/><small>(saloon / manual transmission)</small>!!top speed<br/><small>(saloon / manual transmission)</small>\n|-\n| colspan=\"7\" style=\"text-align:center; background:silver;\"|<big>'''''[[petrol engine]]s'''''</big><br/>all [[fuel injection|fuel injected]]\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|1.6\n|{{convert|102|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{no|}}\n|12.6&nbsp;sec\n|{{convert|118.1|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|1.8 [[turbocharger|T]]\n|{{convert|163|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|8.6&nbsp;sec\n|{{convert|141.7|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|1.8 T [[quattro (four wheel drive system)|quattro]]\n|{{convert|163|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{no|}}\n|8.7&nbsp;sec\n|{{convert|140.5|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|2.0\n|{{convert|130|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{no|}}\n|9.9&nbsp;sec\n|{{convert|131.8|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|2.0 T FSI <ref group=\"B7\" name=\"TFSI\">TFSI combines [[turbocharger]] and [[gasoline direct injection|FSI]]. The badge simply states '''2.0 T''' though.</ref>\n|{{convert|200|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|7.1&nbsp;sec\n|{{convert|149.8|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|2.0 T FSI quattro <ref group=\"B7\" name=\"TFSI\" />\n|{{convert|200|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|7.2&nbsp;sec\n|{{convert|147.9|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|2.0 TFSI DTM <ref group=\"B7\" name=\"TFSI\" /><ref group=\"B7\" name=\"DTM\">In 2005 only available as '''DTM Edition'''. From summer 2006 on available for all saloon and Avant.</ref>\n|{{convert|220|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{no|}}\n|7.0&nbsp;sec\n|{{convert|153.5|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|2.0 TFSI DTM quattro <ref group=\"B7\" name=\"TFSI\" /><ref group=\"B7\" name=\"DTM\" />\n|{{convert|220|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{no|}}\n|6.9&nbsp;sec\n|{{convert|151.7|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|3.2 [[V6 engine|V6]] FSI\n|{{convert|255|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|6.8&nbsp;sec\n|{{convert|155.4|mi/h|0|abbr=on}} <small>(elec. limited)</small>\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|3.2 V6 FSI quattro\n|{{convert|255|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|6.4&nbsp;sec\n|{{convert|155.4|mi/h|0|abbr=on}} <small>(elec. limited)</small>\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|4.2 V8 S4 BBK\n|{{convert|344|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|5.6 sec\n|{{convert|155.4|mi/h|0|abbr=on}} <small>(elec. limited)</small>\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|4.2 V8 RS4\n|{{convert|420|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|4.8 sec\n|{{convert|155.4|mi/h|0|abbr=on}} <small>(elec. limited)</small>\n|-\n| colspan=\"7\" style=\"text-align:center; background:silver;\"|<big>'''''[[diesel engine]]s'''''</big><br/>all [[Turbocharged Direct Injection]] (TDI)\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|1.9 TDI\n|{{convert|115|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{no|}}\n|11.2&nbsp;sec\n|{{convert|124.9|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|2.0 TDI <ref group=\"B7\" name=\"20TDI\">There were two different versions \u2013 one had an 8 valve cylinder head the other had 16 valves. They had the same power and torque output and performed equally. Customers could not choose directly between those two engines. They got the 16-valve version when they ordered the [[Diesel particulate filter|DPF]] otherwise they got the 8-valve version. In many countries the DPF became standard equipment for all B7 diesel engines from model year 2006 on and the 8-valve engine was no more.</ref>\n|{{convert|140|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|9.7&nbsp;sec\n|{{convert|131.8|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|2.0 TDI [[quattro (four wheel drive system)|quattro]]\n|{{convert|140|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|9.7&nbsp;sec\n|{{convert|128.7|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|2.0 TDI\n|{{convert|170|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{no|}}\n|8.6&nbsp;sec\n|{{convert|141.7|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|2.0 TDI quattro\n|{{convert|170|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{no|}}\n|8.5&nbsp;sec\n|{{convert|139.2|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|2.5 [[V6 engine|V6]] TDI <ref group=\"B7\" name=\"25TDI\">Only available for model year 2005. No [[Diesel particulate filter|DPF]] available for this engine. In 2006 replaced by the 2.7 V6 TDI engine.</ref>\n|{{convert|163|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{no|}}\n|8.8&nbsp;sec\n|{{convert|141.1|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|2.7 V6 TDI <ref group=\"B7\" name=\"NEWTDI\" />\n|{{convert|180|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|8.4&nbsp;sec\n|{{convert|142|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|3.0 V6 TDI quattro <ref group=\"B7\" name=\"30TDI\">Only available for model year 2005. In 2006 replaced by a stronger version of the same engine.</ref>\n|{{convert|204|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{no|}}\n|7.2&nbsp;sec\n|{{convert|146|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|3.0 V6 TDI quattro <ref group=\"B7\" name=\"NEWTDI\">Not available before model year 2006.</ref>\n|{{convert|233|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|{{yes|\u2713}}\n|6.8&nbsp;sec\n|{{convert|152.25|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|}\n\n<references group=\"B7\" />\n\n===Safety===\nThe Audi A4 offers many standard safety features, including [[Robert Bosch GmbH|Bosch]] ESP&nbsp;8.0 [[electronic stability control|Electronic Stability Programme]] (ESP) with [[anti-lock braking system]] (ABS), side [[airbag]]s in the seats, 'sideguard' curtain airbags, and its optional [[quattro (four wheel drive system)|quattro]] four-wheel drive system. It also received the [[Insurance Institute for Highway Safety]] (IIHS) \"Top Safety Pick For 2007\".<ref>IIHS.org [http://www.iihs.org/ratings/ratingsbyseries.aspx?id=558 IIHS-HLDI: Audi A4] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011091113/http://www.iihs.org/ratings/ratingsbyseries.aspx?id=558 |date=11 October 2007 }}</ref><ref>IIHS.org [http://www.iihs.org/ratings/tsp_archive.html TOP SAFETY PICK past winners] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070520111723/http://www.iihs.org/ratings/tsp_archive.html |date=20 May 2007 }}</ref> EuroNCAP crash test results from the B6 apply to the B7 model. \n{{clear}}\n\n=={{anchor|B8}}B8 (''Typ'' 8K; 2008\u20132016)==\n{{Infobox automobile\n|name = Fourth generation (B8/8K)\n|image = 2009 Audi A4 (8K MY10) 2.0 TDI sedan (2015-07-09) 01.jpg\n|production = October 2007\u20132015\n|model_years = 2008\u20132016\n|assembly = {{Unbulleted list |Germany: [[Ingolstadt]] |Germany: [[Neckarsulm]] |India: [[Aurangabad, Maharashtra|Aurangabad]] ([[Audi India]]; CKD)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.automobilesreview.com/auto-news/audi-starts-production-audi-a4-india/5106/|title=Audi A4 CKD assembled in India too}}</ref> |China: [[Changchun]] ([[FAW-VW]]) |Indonesia: [[Purwakarta]] ([[Garuda Mataram Motor|Garuda Mataram]])}}\n|designer = Julian H\u00f6enig (exterior: 2004, 2005)<ref>http://www.julianhoenig.com/art/about_files/portfolio.pdf</ref><br>Ingo Von Bargen (interior: 2005)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carbodydesign.com/archive/2007/11/07-audi-a4-design/|title=Audi A4: the design|work=carbodydesign.com}}</ref>\n|body_style = 4-door [[sedan (automobile)|saloon/sedan]],<br/>5-door Avant ([[station wagon|estate/wagon]])\n|platform = [[Volkswagen Group B platform#B8|Volkswagen Group MLB platform]]\n|related = [[Audi A5]]<br/>[[Audi S4#B8|Audi S4 (B8)]]<br/>[[Audi RS4#B8|Audi RS4 (B8)]]\n|engine = {{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Inline-four petrol engine\n|1 = 1.8L [[turbocharger|T]][[gasoline direct injection|FSI]] [[inline-four engine|I4]]\n|2 = 2.0L T[[gasoline direct injection|FSI]] I4\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = V6 petrol engine\n|1 = [[List of Volkswagen Group petrol engines#3.0 V6 24v TFSI 213-245kW|3.0L]] [[V6 engine|V6]] [[Supercharger|T]][[Fuel Stratified Injection|FSI]]\n|2 = 3.2L [[V6 engine|V6]] [[gasoline direct injection|FSI]]\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = V8 petrol engine\n|1 = 4.2L [[V8 engine|V8]] FSI\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Inline-four diesel engine\n|1 = 2.0L [[Turbocharged Direct Injection|TDI]] I4\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = V6 diesel engine\n|1 = 2.7L V6 [[Turbocharged Direct Injection|TDI]]\n|2 = 3.0L V6 [[Turbocharged Direct Injection|TDI]]\n}}\n|transmission = {{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Manual Transmission\n|1 = 6-speed [[manual transmission|Manual]]\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Automatic Transmission\n|1 = 6-speed [[automatic transmission|Tiptronic]]\n|2 = 8-speed [[automatic transmission|automatic]]\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Dual-clutch Transmission\n|1 = 7-speed [[Direct-Shift Gearbox|S tronic]]\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Continuously Variable Transmission\n|1 = 8-speed [[continuously variable transmission|Multitronic]]\n}}\n|wheelbase = {{convert|2808|mm|1|abbr=on}}<br/>allroad: {{convert|2805|mm|1|abbr=on}}<br/>LWB: {{convert|2869|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n|length = {{convert|4703|mm|1|abbr=on}}<br/>allroad: {{convert|4721|mm|1|abbr=on}}<br/>LWB: {{convert|4763|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n|width = {{convert|1826|mm|1|abbr=on}}<br/>allroad: {{convert|1841|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n|height = {{convert|1427|mm|1|abbr=on}}<br/>Avant: {{convert|1436|mm|1|abbr=on}}<br/>allroad: {{convert|1495|mm|1|abbr=on}}<br/>LWB: {{convert|1426|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n|weight =\n|sp = uk\n|predecessor =\n|successor =\n}}\n{{Multiple image | align = left | direction = vertical | width =\n| image1 = Audi A4 allroad quattro Phantomschwarz.JPG\n| image2 = Audi A4 allroad 2.0 TFSI quattro S tronic Gletscherwei\u00df Heck.JPG\n| caption2 = allroad quattro (pre-facelift)\n}}\n\n[[File:2012 Audi A4 B8 interior.jpg|thumbnail|left|Interior]]\nAudi released the first official pictures of the [[Volkswagen Group B platform#B8|B8]] series A4 in August 2007, and unveiled the car to the public at the September 2007 [[Frankfurt Motor Show]]. [[sedan (automobile)|Saloon/sedan]] and Avant ([[station wagon|estate/wagon]]) models are offered. The Avant was unveiled to the public at the March 2008 [[Geneva Motor Show]]. For North America destined models, the B8 continued in production for the 2016 model year, while Europe began deliveries on the 2016 B9 model.\n\nThe B8 A4 is built on a variant of the [[Volkswagen Group MLB platform|Audi Modular Longitudinal Platform]], a platform which is also used in the [[Audi A5]] [[coup\u00e9]]. While prior A4 chassis were limited in [[wheelbase]] due to the relationship between the engine, transmission and front axle, the MLP allows for a reduced front overhang, resulting in a greater wheelbase length without the same increase in overall length.<ref>{{Citation | last =Monticello | first =Mike | title =2009 Audi A4 3.2 Quattro | journal =[[Road & Track]] | volume =60 | issue =2 | page =104 | date =October 2008 | url = | doi = | id = }}</ref> This effectively redistributes the centre of gravity slightly rearwards, improving handling by better balancing vehicle mass between the front and rear axles. The estimated static front:rear weight ratio of the B8 A4 is approximately 55:45, depending on body style and engine. The relocation of the steering rack in front of the axle also improves handling over previous A4 platforms.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} Key to the implementation of MLB is the novel mounting of the [[Differential (mechanical device)|differential]] in front of the clutch. This is achieved by driving the flywheel/clutch remotely by means of a 'top hat' shaped drive plate, between which the differential lay shaft passes, whilst power transmission to the final drive is via an inclined transfer shaft which runs the length of the transmission unit. Whilst the platform retains Audi's \"overhung\" engine mounting position, the front axle is now 152mm further forward than the previous B6/B7 generation platform.<ref>{{cite book|title=Audi A5 \u2013 Self Study Programme|date=January 2007|publisher=Audi AG|page=30|url=http://training.avme.net/admin/Upload/SSP/4801_392%20Audi%20A5%20generell.pdf|accessdate=5 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150105113255/http://training.avme.net/admin/Upload/SSP/4801_392%20Audi%20A5%20generell.pdf|archive-date=5 January 2015|url-status = dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The transfer shaft, however, has the effect of creating a large \"bulge\" on one side of the transmission tunnel, which on right-hand drive versions forces the pedals to be badly offset, which has attracted criticism from the British motoring press in particular.\n\nThe B8 A4 has increased in wheelbase by {{convert|160|mm|in|1}} and in length by {{convert|117|mm|in|1}} over the prior B7, which has allowed for increased rear seating legroom. Although the overall dimensions have increased, the kerb weight has dropped some 10%. The boot (trunk) has also increased to {{convert|480|L|cuft|1}} for the saloon (sedan) version. The A4 Avant will have a maximum capacity of {{convert|1430|L|cuft|1|abbr=on}} with the rear seats folded down.\n\nReception has been mixed, with praise for the Audi A4's increased size, giving it best-in-class rear legroom and trunk space in the compact executive car segment.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iol.co.za/motoring/latest-launches/audi-a4-replacement-hot-and-cool-1.852835|title=Audi A4 replacement: Hot and cool|last=Rutherford|first=Mike|date=6 November 2007|work=iol.co.za|accessdate=11 May 2011}}</ref> Its inline-4 2.0 TFSI engine, while efficient providing plenty of torque, was considered lacking and less refined compared to 6-cylinder engines of lighter rivals who posted faster acceleration times. However, the [[Audi S4]] [[sports sedan]] has been well-received for its V6 3.0 TFSI engine's power and efficiency.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/27/automobiles/27ulrich-best.html?pagewanted=2&_r=1&sq=Ford%20Taurus%20disappointing&st=cse&scp=1 | work=The New York Times | title=A Holiday From Wishful Thinking | first=Lawrence | last=Ulrich | date=27 December 2009 | accessdate=2 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/08/automobiles/autoreviews/08audi-a4.html?_r=1&pagewanted=2 | work=The New York Times | first=Lawrence | last=Ulrich | title=A Class Act Matures in Size and Price | date=8 February 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newcartestdrive.com/review-intro.cfm?Vehicle=2009_Audi_A4&ReviewID=4525 |title=2009 Audi A4 Review, Prices, Photos |publisher=New Car Test Drive |accessdate=11 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe B8 A4 was facelifted in early 2012.\n\nDuring a model cycle changes are made to integrate new technologies and to keep the model competitive. These changes are referenced based on the model year (MY) of the car.\nIn Australia, the B8 has undergone 2 revisions leading to three variants, the B8, B8 MY10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ozaudi.com/forums/showthread.php/19978-MY10-changes-for-Australian-Audi-range |title=MY10 changes for Australian Audi range |publisher=Ozaudi.com |date= |accessdate=2011-05-16}}</ref> and B8 MY11.\n\n===Body types===\n{{Multiple image | align = left | direction = vertical | width = 200\n| image1 = Audi A4 B8 2.0 TDI 20090906 rear.JPG\n| caption1 = Sedan (pre-facelift)\n| image2 = 2009-2010 Audi A4 (8K) 2.7 TDI Avant (2011-01-12).jpg\n| caption2 = Avant (pre-facelift)\n| image3 = Audi A4L B8 02 China 2012-04-14.jpg\n| caption3 = A4L (pre-facelift)\n}}\n\n====Saloon / Sedan ====\nAudi released the first official pictures of the [[Volkswagen Group B platform#B8|B8]] series A4 in August 2007, and unveiled the car to the public at the September 2007 [[Frankfurt Motor Show]]. [[sedan (automobile)|Saloon/sedan]] and Avant ([[station wagon|estate/wagon]]) models are offered.\n\n====Avant====\nThe Avant station wagon / estate was presented at the March 2008 [[Geneva Motor Show]].\n\n====A4L====\nThe A4L is a long-wheelbase version for the Chinese market, with a {{convert|60|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} longer wheelbase and length.<ref>PaulTan.org [http://paultan.org/archives/2008/11/17/new-extended-audi-a4l-for-the-china-market/ New extended Audi A4L for the China market]</ref> The vehicle was presented at the 2008 Guangzhou Motor Show. The production version then went on sale in January 2009. Launch models included a 2.0 TFSI with 132&nbsp;kW (180&nbsp;hp) and the 3.2 FSI with 195&nbsp;kW (265&nbsp;hp).<ref>{{cite web|last=Filipponio |first=Frank |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2008/11/17/audi-intros-long-wheelbase-a4-for-china/ |title=Audi intros long-wheelbase A4L for China |publisher=Autoblog.com |date=17 November 2008 |accessdate=2010-10-20}}</ref>\n\n====A4 allroad quattro====\nThe '''A4 allroad quattro''' features a wider track, increased ground clearance, quattro permanent [[four-wheel drive]], a distinctive radiator grille, stainless steel underbody guards and roof rails.\n\nThe A4 allroad quattro was made available in early summer 2009.<ref name=\"allroad-pr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.audi.com/com/brand/en/company/news/models_and_services.detail.2009~02~the_audi_a4_allroad.html |title=The Audi A4 allroad quattro: A Vehicle that knows no Boundaries |date=15 February 2009 |work=www.audi.com |publisher=Audi AG |accessdate=2009-02-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221142116/http://www.audi.com/com/brand/en/company/news/models_and_services.detail.2009~02~the_audi_a4_allroad.html |archivedate=21 February 2009 |url-status = live}}</ref>\nThe car was unveiled in 2009 [[Geneva Motor Show]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Paukert |first=Chris |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2009/03/04/geneva-2009-new-audi-a4-allroad-debuts-reportedly-may-come-to/ |title=Geneva 2009: New Audi A4 Allroad debuts, reportedly may come to U.S. after all |publisher=Autoblog.com |date=3 April 2009 |accessdate=2010-10-20}}</ref>\n\n===Specifications===\n\n====Body styles====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Body !!Sedan !!Avant !!A4L!!allroad quattro\n|-\n|Year ||2011\u2013||2010\u2013||2009||\n|-\n|Luggage capacity||{{convert|480|L|cuft|1}} with the rear seats in the upright position, and {{convert|962|L|cuft|1|abbr=on}} with the seats folded||{{convert|490|L|cuft|1|abbr=on}} with the rear seats upright, and {{convert|1430|L|cuft|1|abbr=on}} with the seats folded||?||